    "text": "Probabilistic evaluation metrics such as the Brier score or logarithmic score compare probability predictions to binary outcomes without requiring thresholding of the probability map.",
    "topic": "Probabilistic metrics without thresholding"
  },
  {
    "text": "A discrete classification map can be treated as a binary indicator variable for each class, thereby providing observed outcomes against which probabilistic predictions can be scored.",
    "topic": "Discrete map as binary outcomes"
  },
  {
    "text": "Converting a continuous probability map to a discrete classification map via a threshold makes the comparison dependent on the chosen threshold, potentially confounding the assessment of the probability map's quality.",
    "topic": "Thresholding confounds accuracy"
  },
  {
    "text": "An apples‑to‑apples comparison is achieved by using evaluation metrics that honor the continuous nature of the probability map and the categorical nature of the discrete map, not by forcing both maps into the same data type.",
    "topic": "Apples‑to‑apples with appropriate metrics"
  }
]
